# Copy to .env and set your keys. Never commit .env.
#
# Local dev: `npm run dev` runs scripts/dev-server.cjs (static files + /api/weather like Vercel).
# Use `npm run serve:static` only if you do not need the weather proxy.
#
# ── OpenWeatherMap (live forecasts in the app) ───────────────────────────────
# OPENWEATHER_API_KEY — paste the **secret key string** from https://home.openweathermap.org/api_keys
# (the “Name” column, e.g. usaloop, is only a label in the dashboard — it is not used in API calls).
# (Free tier: Current weather + 5 day / 3 hour forecast). If you see HTTP 401, the key is wrong
# or not activated yet (OpenWeather states up to ~2 hours after creation).
# On Vercel: add OPENWEATHER_API_KEY under Project → Settings → Environment Variables
# (no need to expose it to the browser build).
#
# ── Google Maps Platform (map, Directions, distances) ─────────────────────────
# GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY — Browser Maps JavaScript API key (AIza…). Restrict with
# Application restrictions → HTTP referrers (localhost, 127.0.0.1, production domain).
# Enable: Maps JavaScript API, Directions API (legacy), Places if used.
#
# GOOGLE_MAPS_SERVER_KEY — Optional separate key for any server-side Google calls
# (not used for weather anymore). Often omitted.
#
# GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID — OAuth web client id (…apps.googleusercontent.com). Injected at build.
# GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET — Server-only; never ship to the client.
#
# Vercel: set GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY, OPENWEATHER_API_KEY, optional GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID for the build.
# Push this file's keys to the linked Vercel project: npm run env:push (skips VERCEL_*).

GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY=
GOOGLE_MAPS_SERVER_KEY=
OPENWEATHER_API_KEY=
GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=
GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=
